  "assistantText": "Circuit built successfully! Here's the full breakdown:\n\n---\n\n## 🔌 Wiring Table\n\n| Arduino Pin | Component | Role |\n|---|---|---|\n| **D12** | LED1 (Red) Anode | LED1 output |\n| — | R1 (220Ω) | LED1 cathode → GND rail |\n| **D11** | LED2 (Blue) Anode | LED2 output |\n| — | R2 (220Ω) | LED2 cathode → GND rail |\n| **D2** | BTN1 Signal pin | Button input (reads HIGH when pressed) |\n| **5V** | BTN1 VCC pin | Powers button when pressed |\n| **GND** | BTN1 GND pin | Button low side |\n| **GND** | R3 (10kΩ) | Pull-down: holds D2 LOW when button open |\n\n---\n\n## 📋 Sketch Logic\n\n| State | LED1 | LED2 |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Button NOT pressed** | Blinks slowly (700ms) | OFF |\n| **Button HELD** | ON solid | ON solid |\n\n---\n\n## ⚡ Power Budget Summary\n\n| Source | Load | Current | Pin Safe? |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| D12 → LED1 → R1 (220Ω) | (5V − 2.0V) / 220Ω | **~13.6 mA** | ✅ < 20mA |\n| D11 → LED2 → R2 (220Ω) | (5V − 2.0V) / 220Ω | **~13.6 mA** | ✅ < 20mA |\n| D2 → BTN input | Pulled via 10kΩ to GND | **~0.5 mA** | ✅ negligible |\n| **Total draw** | Both LEDs on simultaneously | **~27 mA** | ✅ Well within Uno's 200mA rail limit |\n\n> 💡 **Design notes:**\n> - The **10kΩ pull-down** on D2 ensures a clean LOW when the button is open — prevents floating/noisy reads.\n> - **220Ω** limits each LED to ~13–14 mA — safe for Arduino I/O pins and gives good brightness.\n> - GND and 5V **rails are shared** across all components via the breadboard power rails.",
